review_blob: Deep amber, somewhat cloudy; has an excellent malty aroma with caramel tones; full-bodied, bitter taste but not too much; fabulous

Golden brown, copper in colour; little or no traces of gas rising; has a fabulous aroma, very earthy, somewhat fruity; I found the taste intensely bitter at first, the earthy tones are full on in the taste, smooth/soft in the mouth, almost flat when it comes to the gas; aftertaste has the same bitterness, but does not longer too much

Darker shade of brown, clear traces of gas rising; Very nutty, malted brown bread aroma; strong blast of deep, bitterness fills the mouth (almost overpowering), has that deep roasted nuttiness (not sure which type of nut) in the flavour; Rich bitterness in the aftertaste

Clear, dark tan in colour; fabulous but subtle aroma; rather robust and strong in its taste, you get that smoky taste in there, malty, slightly bitter, somewhat burnt; slightly harsh in after-taste with that burnt malt taste.

Deep, very dark black in colour; essence of treacle in aroma with wisps of malt combining to give a sweet scent; very smooth dark roasted taste, you get the traces of treacle in there but it is the strong, deep roasted bitterness that envelops the mouth

Light amber in colour with clear traces of gas rising; light hoppy aroma with a sweet, honey infusion; light to taste but with plenty of honey taste, no bitterness, not much in the way of hoppiness, in fact not much else other than honey; really cant tell if there is an after taste.

Rich, deep black in color, opaque enough not to see anything through it; thick vanilla coloured head; Rich roasted aroma; Deep, roasted malt, traces of chocolate and coffee, smooth to taste with interesting elements of bitterness; a roasted. malty after taste.

Murky, dark tan, that you can just about see through; is has a strong but pleasant malty aroma that pleases the nose; its taste is surprising robust, it has a mashup of bitterness, maltyness and some complex elements to it, there is some roasted undertones that give way to the complex bitterness t

5.9% Abv, 16.9, 24 IBU; A slightly dark caramel-brown in colour, visible fizz rising, but not too much; it has a caramel aroma; the caramel is brought through into the taste with elements of a rich-roasting of the malt, it then gives was to a pleasant bitterness that I would not say is overly bitter for my palate; a caramel aftertaste.

Dark, cloudy, almost molasses in colour (reminds me of a dark, unfiltered wheat beer); hoppy traces in the aroma, but with strong blasts of rich, dark roasted barley; Has arich roatsed flavour, with an almost nutty element, very smooth; Plenty of roasted bitter after taste.

It has that deep, Garnet colour, with a somewhat hoppy aroma; Bitter, somewhat acidic taste with hoppy elements somewhere in there, overly gassy; light watery aftertaste with a residual butterness that seems to leave this strange linger acidity on the tongue

Pale, gold in colour, frothy head that is quick to disappear; Light, somewhat hoppy smell; Light, gassy taste, that has a trace of hops and a slight bitterness, but not much else; the aftertaste is at least not a clinging one and someone watery.

Golden amber in colour; Hoppy, somewhat nutty aroma, combined with an element of rich maltings; this is carried through to the taste that is both rich and full bodied with the strength and nuttiness that then gives way to a slightly bitter but not too tongue arresting; rich roasted aftertaste with residual bitterness.

golden in color, solid enough head even from the bottle, plenty of gas rising; A strong, rich aroma, somewhat a blend of malt and hops in equal amounts, but tending towards to distinctly grainy malt aroma; the malty element is carried into the taste, but tends towards to the bitter side which lasts, slightly water; the palate is full-on and solid, but is too gassy for my taste; the bitterness stays in the mouth for quite a while.

Fabulously malty aroma; darker, brown-amber in colour; full bodied, nutty, malty; somewhat gassy, but subtly so; slightly sweeter aftertaste, but certainly bitter, exceptionally rich. Not too much in the bottle though

Pale, gold in colour with a fair amount of gas rising; wonderfully fresh aroma, light hoppy with elements of grass; Quite bitter, somewhat harsh but still has elements of freshness in there; medium texture, somewhat medium body, plenty of fizz.

A pale ale brewed with "Pale and Crystal malts combined with a delicate combination of Pioneer, Styrian Goldings and Lubelski hops". Once it settles your mouth greets the flavour with enthusiasm. Not too gassy, just right.
beer_name: Purple Moose Snowdonia Ale / Cwrw Eryri

review_blob: Its dark golden in colour and has a richer roasted, malty taste, somewhat to the point of being burnt, or on the point of it. Really pleasant and certainly (by a long way) the better Gambrinus.

Light, golden colour, very gassy, light taste. To be honest, very light in taste. This was not a very good taste, in fact I didnt even finish it - a few mouth fulls were enough to convince me not to drink any more. Far too light in flavour, more like beer flavoured water.
Light, golden colour, very gassy, light taste. This is nasty, but not as nasty as Gambrinus Svetly.

Almost the same in colour to other Pilsners; wonderful yeasty aroma; even from the bottle maintains the head; taste is rather sharp; pleasant enough after taste; I would say a slightly heavier taste, put it this way you know you are drinking something different.

Best on tap, acceptable in a bottle. Light golden, slightly misty in colour- usual of wheat beers; smells good, very light and wheaty; taste is really great, reminds me of Belgian and German white beers, it has a very pleasant taste; refreshing.

You know you are drinking this because it wrestles your taste buds of the mouth.  The taste is heavy, not too heavy, but you know that this is more of a sipping beer than gulping. It needs to be savoured. Does have the usual dark, roasted flavour the dark (Tmavy) beers have, but the simple strength of the beer washes it quickly away.

Dark, rich tan in colour; run the beer through the mouth and you get an effervescent taste; It has a rich taste, not too strong, but rich enough to let you know that you are drinking something worth drinking.

Rich, dark brown, almost molasses in colour (I reckoned it looked like crude oil); not too much fizz; a sweet taste at first, then giving way to a more bitter, dark roasted, almost coffee-treacle taste; strange chemical aftertaste,
has a light, yeasty, hoppy smell to it; a light, golden brown colour; a light, plenty of fizz taste without being too gassy, not bitter, but somewhat empty

You need to try this on tap, bottled version does not do it justice. Pale in colour, light, golden brown; solid head (even from bottle); smells really good, certainly a fruity aroma; Solid, hoppy taste, really smooth body, actually has great substance. Pleasant after taste, not too heavy or mouth souring.

Pale, light golden in colour; subtle hops and barley mix, not too strong in odour; subtle fizz, theres plenty there but its not a mouth full of bubbles experience, rather soft; delicious, earthy taste, not too strong, not too light; has a bit of an aftertaste, but not over powering.
Hand pumped; a light-pale amber pint of beer, slightly cloudy; light, or actually little, gas, subtle effervescence; Bitter, in fact dry bitterness, hoppy taste.
Dark brown, they call it deep ruby; dark roasted hop smell, somewhat sweet vapours come from it; deep, rich bitter taste, rich after taste; light fizz, deliciously rich body
beer_name: Purple Moose Dark Side Of The Moose / Ochr Dywyll Y Mws

review_blob: Deep, golden brown; has a fabulous, Christmas scent (Christmas pud or mince pies); Bitter, but with a somewhat fruity taste; pleasant fizz fills the mouth with essence of cinnamon
beer_name: Purple Moose Merry X-Moose / X-Mws Llawen

review_blob: I really like this. Light, golden brown in colour; has an almost honey smell to it, bitter, malty; tastes pretty much as it smells with a delicious honey-malt taste to it; slightly bitter after taste; light fizz.
Not the greatest example of EPA. Light aroma of hops; murky-brown-amber in colour; light taste; very fizzy
Light, golden brown in colour, clear; fabulous hoppy, golden malt smell; Similar taste to smell, malty, hoppy, pleasant fizz and pleasant bitter aftertaste.

Has a fabulous aroma to it, I am getting apricots somehow, and a definite roasted scent, the smell is quite fabulous; golden brown in colour; first taste is rather a full on blow, I get the apricots again, that roasted flavour comes at you and then the bitterness kicks in, not over powering but you can certainly tell it has a great flavour, quite a presence; after taste isnt too bad, you still get the bitterness but not too much.

Fine hoppy flavour, you can get the malt and barley there too, clean smell; light gold, amber in colour; solid, full-on taste to it, you get the hops and roastings in there, rounded fizz, heavier on the bitter side but not too much so; distinct bitter after taste.
Strong in hops, almost fruity; light gold, amber, strong traces of bubbles; Bitter to taste, plenty of gas, bitter after taste
Pale, light golden with a slight haze; has a fruity scent of hops, malt; has an initial bitter taste that gives way to rounded hops taste, slight bitter after taste

Gives off a distinctive aroma, almost a heavy set hops smell; cloudy in appearance, otherwise it is quite cloudy; taste is somewhat interesting, it goes from an initial lightness, slight bitterness, then almost watery, then as you swallow you get the subtle bitterness. Interesting.

Amber, light-gold, traces of bubbles rising; has a clear, crisp aroma to it, you get the hops there from the beginning but not an over powering scent; certainly a full hoppy taste, medium bitter from the start to the end, pleasant without taking over the mouth; bitter after taste followed by some sweetness. Better on tap, acceptable in the bottle

Certainly cloudy with a solid foam head, little or no gas rising; rich smell, hoppy, yeasty certainly a good beer smell, nothing light; the taste is interestingly complex, it has a mashy, yeasty taste, somewhat fresh to start out with and then the bitters rampage across the tongue giving a rounded and fabulously pleasant taste; this taste lasts and fills the mouth for some time.

Dark, amber cloudy beer that even has a good head of froth on top from the bottle; you really get the wheatiness about it, almost a golden sweetness about it; quite a light bitterness at first that gives way to an all enveloping classic wheat-beer taste, plenty of fizz at just the right amounts, generous amounts of bitterness

Probably not doing it enough justice; fluffy head which didnt last too long, clearly hoppy, some fruitiness in there; slightly darker amber, very faint wisps of gas rising; bitter, quite gassy, generous roasting, plenty of hops, full flavour.
distinct but clear hoppy aroma; light amber; lighter in taste, rounded in gas but not too much because it was on tap; biter aftertaste, but not a long linger mouth wash.

This is one of those beers that should only be tried from the tap; robust almost nutty aroma with some complex essences; A smooth and complex taste, I found it was somewhat buttery as an initial taste with some amounts of bitterness, but the overall taste masks somewhat the strength. Fabulous

hoppy smell, nothing too strong; has a full flavour that is certainly complete in body and a somewhat bready taste, you certainly get grains and roastings in there, but leads into a pleasant, full tasting beer; not too bitter after taste, I am still getting bread.

Dark molasses in colour, its like a thick treacle; Rich sweetness and a dark roasted smell rises out as soon as you pour; It has all that darkness in taste too, you get the roasting in there and the bitterness is tempered by the subtle sweetness; you get a slightly bitter aftertaste but it almost heads in to that chocolate flavour.

It has a dark roasted, hoppy scent; dark, malted brown in colour; It has the distinctive sweet, darker roasted floavour to it, some bitterness which is masked by the sweetness; the bitterness and sweet taste does not mask the chemical aftertaste.

hoppy taste, didnt give off too much in the glass then again I am terrible when it comes to pouring it out; golden brown in colour; fabulously bitter taste; malt and hops in there which doesnt get drowned out by the bitter taste, plenty of fizz but pleasantly so.
The bottle lets it down. The taste makes up for the rest; solid enough and full bodied
